1. Introduction 
Let L_0^2(P) denote the zero mean square integrable functions on some probability space. The stochastic processes in this paper are either discrete time (T=‚Ñ§) or continuous time (T=‚Ñù) and they are subsets of L_0^2(P). Let T^=Œ†‚âî‚Ñù/2*œÄ*‚Ñ§=(-œÄ,œÄ] if T=‚Ñ§ and T^=‚Ñù if T=‚Ñù, and let ùîπ denote the Borel œÉ-field of either Œ† or ‚Ñù.
Recall that a process (X_t)_(t‚ààT) is weakly stationary if its covariance function admits the representation
Cov(X_s,X_t)=int_(T^)e^(i*Œª*s)(e^(i*Œª*t))¬Ø Œº*(d*Œª), s,t‚ààT  (1)
where Œº is a finite positive measure on T^.
Harmonizable processes are an extension which allow also for these Fourier methods. A stochastic process (X_t)_(t‚ààT) is called strongly harmonizable if its covariance function admits the representation
Cov(X_s,X_t)=int_(T^)int_(T^)e^(i*s*Œª)(e^(i*t*Œª'))¬Ø Œ≤(d*Œª,d*Œª'), ‚àÄs,t‚ààT  (2)
for some measure Œ≤ on ùîπ‚äóùîπ. These processes were introduced by Lo√®ve (1948) and Cram√©r (1951). An important example of strongly harmonizable processes are the periodically correlated discrete time processes (Hurd, 1989, 1991; Dehay, 1994). In this case, the mass of Œ≤ is concentrated on lines parallel to the diagonal {(Œª,Œª),Œª‚ààT^} of T^√óT^. However, the class of strongly harmonizable processes is still not large enough for some applications. For example, it is not closed under linear transformations. A wider extension of stationary processes are the weakly harmonizable processes. These processes have the same covariance representation as strongly harmonizable processes, but the conditions on Œ≤ are relaxed. Œ≤ is not necessarily a measure, but can be a bimeasure (i.e., Œ≤ is a mapping Œ≤:ùîπ√óùîπ‚Üí‚ÑÇ and Œ≤(‚ãÖ,A),Œ≤(A,‚ãÖ) are measures for all A‚ààùîπ), which is positive definite (i.e., Œ≤(A,B)=(Œ≤(B,A))¬Ø and sum_(i,j)a_i*Œ≤(A_i,A_j)(a_j)¬Ø‚â•0 for all A_i‚ààùîπ,a_i‚àà‚ÑÇ). Œ≤ is called the spectral bimeasure of the process. The class of weakly harmonizable processes is closed under linear transformations. Indeed, another characterization of weakly harmonizability is that these processes are coordinatewise images of stationary processes under linear mappings (Niemi, 1975, 1977). In general, bimeasures cannot be extended to measures on T^‚äóT^, so the integral above is not a Lebesgue integral, but a strict integral in the sense of Morse and Transue (Chang and Rao, 1986).
Let f,g:T^‚Üí‚ÑÇ be measurable and Œ≤ a bimeasure on ùîπ√óùîπ. (f,g) is strictly Œ≤-integrable, if
1.f is Œ≤(‚ãÖ,A)-integrable, g is Œ≤(A,‚ãÖ)-integrable for all A‚ààùîπ. If this holds, then Œ≤_1^E:A‚Ü¶int_Ef(x)*Œ≤(d*x,A) and Œ≤_2^F:A‚Ü¶int_Fg(y)*Œ≤(A,d*y) are measures for all E,F‚ààŒ£ (Houdr√©, 1987, Lemma 2).
2.f is Œ≤_2^F-integrable and g is Œ≤_1^E-integrable for all E,F‚ààùîπ.
One defines now
int_Eint_F^‚àó(f,g)* d*Œ≤‚âîint_Ef(x)*Œ≤_2^F*(d*x)=int_Fg(y)*Œ≤_1^E*(d*y)  (3)
The equality of the integrals holds by Houdr√© (1987, Theorem 4). If Œ≤ is a measure on ùîπ‚äóùîπ and f,g are bounded, then this integral is equal to the usual Lebesgue integral, i.e., int_Eint_Ff(x)*g(y)*Œ≤(d*x,d*y).
For a positive-definite bimeasure Œ≤ define
L_‚àó^2(Œ≤)‚âî{f:(f,f¬Ø)*is strict Œ≤-integrable}  (4)
the spectral domain of Œ≤. This is a pre-Hilbert space with the inner product
(f,g)_Œ≤‚âîiint^‚àó(f,g¬Ø)* d*Œ≤  (5)
(cf. Chang and Rao, 1986).
Now let (X_t)_(t‚ààT) be a weakly harmonizable process with spectral bimeasure Œ≤. As for a stationary process, (X_t)_(t‚ààT) has an integral representation
X_t=int_(T^)e^(i*Œª*t)*Z*(d*Œª)  (6)
where Z is a stochastic measure (i.e., L_0^2(P)-valued) and the integral is in the sense of Dunford-Schwartz (1960, IV.10). Z is called the stochastic spectral measure of (X_t)_(t‚ààT). It is related to the spectral bimeasure by
Œ≤(A,B)=E(Z(A) (Z(B))¬Ø)  (7)
L_‚àó^2(Œ≤)=L^1(Z)  (8)
and
Cov(intf* d*Z,intg* d*Z)=iint^‚àó(f,g¬Ø)* d*Œ≤  (9)
(Chang and Rao, 1986). We then say that Œ≤ is induced by Z.
It is well-known that
H_Z‚âî(sp{Z(A),A‚ààùîπ})¬Ø=(sp{int_(T^)e^(i*t‚ãÖ)*d*Z, t‚ààT})¬Ø  (10)
Indeed, stochastic measures on T^ are regular (Dunford and Schwartz, 1960, IV.10.5) and hence the set of integrals of continuous functions is dense in H_Z. The assertion now follows from the fact that continuous functions can be approximated uniformly on compact sets by trigonometric polynomials (Naimark, 1959, p. 406, Corollary 4).
As we have already seen, the mapping
V:L_‚àó^2(Œ≤)‚ÜíH_Z, f‚Ü¶intf* d*Z  (11)
is an isometry. It is easy to see that V is surjective if and only if L_‚àó^2(Œ≤) is complete. Thus, the spectral domain and the time domain of the process are isometrically isomorphic if and only if the spectral domain is complete.
One of the reasons to introduce weakly harmonizable processes was to retain the powerful Fourier methods of the stationary processes, so that, for example, extrapolation and interpolation can be carried out in the spectral domain of the process, using again the methods of Fourier analysis. But the transition from the spectral domain to the time domain of a process can only be made in full generality if the spectral domain is complete.
Cram√©r, who defined the spectral domain, raised the problem of the completeness of this spectral domain: ‚Äúthe set Œõ_2(œÅ) will have all the properties of Hilbert space, except possibly the completeness property‚Äù (Cram√©r, 1951).
The following result due to Rao (Rao, 1989, p. 605, Proposition 3.2) gives a sufficient condition for the completeness of the spectral domain of a weakly harmonizable process (with T=‚Ñù or ‚Ñ§): Let Œ≤ be a positive-definite bimeasure on ùîπ√óùîπ. Then L_‚àó^2(Œ≤) is complete if there is a positive finite measure Œº on ùîπ and a continuous linear mapping W:L^2(Œº)‚ÜíL^2(Œº) with closed range such that L^2(Œº)‚äÇL_‚àó^2(Œ≤) and
iint^‚àó(f,g¬Ø)* d*Œ≤=intW(f)(W(g))¬Ø d*Œº, ‚àÄf,g‚ààL^2(Œº)  (12)
This is always true for some Œº and some W, but the range may not be closed. If L^2(Œº)=L_‚àó^2(Œ≤), the closed range condition is necessary. The closed range condition is clearly satisfied if there are constants C,c>0 such that
C‚Äñf‚Äñ_(Œº,2)‚â•‚Äñf‚Äñ_Œ≤‚â•c‚Äñf‚Äñ_(Œº,2), ‚àÄf‚ààL^2(Œº)  (13)
Theorem 1. 1.‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z‚âîsup_(|g|‚â§|f|)|intg* d*Z|, f‚ààL^1(Z), is a norm on L^1(Z). This norm is equivalent to the norm
‚Äñ‚Äñ*f‚Äñ‚Äñ‚âîsup_(A‚ààŒ£)|int_Af* d*Z|‚â•1/4‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z  (14)
2.(L^1(Z),‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Z) is a Banach space.
3.If f_n,f‚ààL^1(Z) for all n‚àà‚Ñï and lim_(n‚Üí‚àû)‚Äñf-f_n‚Äñ_Z=0, then (f_n)_(n‚àà‚Ñï) converges to f in Z-measure (i.e., for all Œµ>0, lim_(n‚Üí‚àû)‚ÄñZ‚Äñ({|f_n-f|>Œµ})=0). Hence any subsequence of (f_n)_(n‚àà‚Ñï) contains a subsequence converging Z-almost everywhere to f.
2. A condition for the completeness of the spectral domain 
Theorem 1. Let ‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Œ≤=0 be equivalent to ‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Z=0. Then the following statements are equivalent:
1.L_‚àó^2(Œ≤) is complete.
2.There exists K>0 such that for all f‚ààL^1(Z),
K‚Äñf‚Äñ_Œ≤‚â•‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z  (15)
3.There exists a positive finite measure Œº and constants c,C>0 such that L^2(Œº)=L^1(Z)=L_‚àó^2(Œ≤) and
C‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_(Œº,2)‚â•‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Œ≤‚â•c‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_(Œº,2)  (16)
Let |f|_Z‚âîinf_(|h|=|f|)‚Äñinth* d*Z‚Äñ=inf_(|h|=|f|)‚Äñh‚Äñ_Œ≤. For f,g‚ààL^1(Z) and f*g=0,
‚Äñf+g‚Äñ_Z^2 =sup_(|f'|‚â§|f|,|g'|‚â§|g|) sup_(Œ±‚àà‚ÑÇ,|Œ±|=1)[(Œ±*f',Œ±*f')_Œ≤+(g',g')_Œ≤+2Re(Œ±*f',g')_Œ≤] (17)
