and in a similar way |f+g|_Z^2‚â§|f|_Z^2+|g|_Z^2.
Define
Œº(A)‚âîsup {sum_i|1_(A_i)|_Z^2 ; (A_i)*finite measurable partition of A}  (20)
For a simple function f,
|f|_Z^2‚â§‚Äñf‚Äñ_(Œº,2)^2‚â§‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z^2  (21)
If K>0 such that K‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Œ≤‚â•‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Z, then for all f‚ààL^1(Z),
K|f|_Z=K*inf_(|g|=|f|)‚Äñg‚Äñ_Œ≤‚â•inf_(|g|=|f|)‚Äñg‚Äñ_Z=‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z  (22)
Hence, the norms ‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_(Œº,2) and ‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Z are equivalent for the simple functions and thus for all of L^1(Z)=L^2(Œº).
Let Z^ be the orthogonally scattered Hilbert space valued measure with
‚ÄñZ^(A)‚Äñ^2=Œº(A), L^1(Z^)=L^2(Œº)  (23)
and
(intf* d*Z^,intg* d*Z^)=intf*g¬Ø* d*Œº, ‚àÄf,g‚ààL^2(Œº)  (24)
Let (x_i)_(i‚àà‚Ñï) be a normed sequence in some Hilbert space, and Z the measure on ‚Ñï with Z({i})=x_i/i^2, i‚àà‚Ñï. Then (a_i)_(i‚àà‚Ñï)‚ààL^1(Z) if and only if sum_(i=1)^‚àûa_i*x_i=int_‚Ñïa* d*Z is unconditionally convergent. Theorem 1 thus generalizes the theorem of K√∂the and Toeplitz, which states that if (x_n)_(n‚àà‚Ñï) is a normed unconditional base of a Hilbert space, then there exist constants c,C>0 such that
c*sum_(i=1)^n|a_i|^2‚â§|sum_(i=1)^na_i*x_i|^2‚â§C*sum_(i=1)^n|a_i|^2, a_i‚àà‚ÑÇ, i=1,‚Ä¶,n‚àà‚Ñï  (25)
3. The shift operator condition 
Theorem 2. Let (X_t)_(t‚àà‚Ñ§) be a weakly harmonizable process with spectral bimeasure Œ≤ and stochastic spectral measure Z.
Then the following are equivalent:
1.‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Œ≤=0 is equivalent to ‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Z=0
2.The shift operator S:L_‚àó^2(Œ≤)‚ÜíL_‚àó^2(Œ≤), S(f)‚âîexp (i*‚ãÖ)*f is a well-defined invertible linear mapping, i.e., ‚Äñf‚Äñ_Œ≤=0‚áî‚Äñexp (i‚ãÖ)f‚Äñ_Œ≤=0
Proof. (1) ‚áí (2): This follows immediately from ‚Äñf*e^(i‚ãÖ)‚Äñ_Z=‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z.
(2) ‚áí (1): Let ‚Äñf‚Äñ_Œ≤=0. There is A‚ààùîπ such that ‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z‚â§5*‚Äñf*1_A‚Äñ_Œ≤. Since ‚ÄñZ‚Äñ is regular, there exist trigonometric polynomials (p_n)_(n‚àà‚Ñï) with ‚Äñp_n‚Äñ_‚àû‚â§2 for all n‚àà‚Ñï, such that lim_(n‚Üí‚àû)‚Äñp_n-1_A‚Äñ_Z=0. By dominated convergence, lim_(k‚Üí‚àû) intp_(n_k)*f* d*Z=int_Af* d*Z for some subsequence. If p=sum_(j=-m)^ma_j*e^(i*j‚ãÖ),
|intp*f* d*Z|=‚Äñp*f‚Äñ_Œ≤‚â§sum_(j=-m)^m|a_j|‚ÄñS^j(f)‚Äñ_Œ≤=0  (26)
Hence 0=5‚Äñint_Af* d*Z‚Äñ‚â•‚Äñf‚Äñ_Z.
Remark A sufficient condition for the existence of an invertible shift operator S of the spectral domain is the existence of an invertible shift operator S^ of the time domain H_X‚âîsp{X_t,t‚àà‚Ñ§}, i.e., a continuous linear and invertible mapping S^:H_X‚ÜíH_X with S^(X_t)=X_(t+1) for all t. Indeed, it is sufficient to show that
S^(intf* d*Z)=intS(f)* d*Z, ‚àÄf‚ààL^1(Z)  (27)
If (X_t)_(t‚àà‚Ñ§) is a weakly harmonizable process whose spectral domain is complete and the shift operator S exists and is invertible, then by the last two theorems the operators S^k,k‚àà‚Ñ§, are uniformly bounded.
The following theorem, due to Nagy (1948), gives an affirmative answer (see also Truong-Van, 1981).
Theorem (Nagy) Let (X_t)_(t‚àà‚Ñ§) be a stochastic process, and let S be the shift operator of the process (i.e., S is a linear continuous mapping on the time domain of (X_t)_(t‚àà‚Ñ§), S(X_t)=X_(t+1) for all t). If S is invertible and moreover the mappings S^k,k‚àà‚Ñ§, are uniformly bounded (in the operator norm), then (X_t)_(t‚àà‚Ñ§) is weakly harmonizable and there exists a finite positive measure Œº, such that ‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_(Œº,2) and ‚Äñ‚ãÖ‚Äñ_Œ≤ are equivalent, where Œ≤ is the spectral bimeasure of (X_t)_(t‚àà‚Ñ§). Hence L_‚àó^2(Œ≤) is complete.
